ire, England":"Aldworth, Berkshire, England","Boxford, Berkshire, England":"Boxford, Berkshire, England","Pangbourne, Berkshire, England":"Pangbourne, Berkshire, England","Shouldham, Norfolk, England":"Shouldham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1505–1562":"1505–1562","1503–1555":"1503–1555","1515–1555":"1515–1555","1535–Male":"1535–Deceased","1538–Female":"1538–Deceased","1540–Male":"1540–Deceased","1542–1569":"1542–1569","1545–Female":"1545–Deceased","before 1555":"before 1555","ABT 1545":"about 1545","ABT 1535":"about 1535","ABT 1538":"about 1538","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1545":"1545","1555":"1555","1521":"1521","about 1515":"about 1515","ABT 1540":"about 1540","1542":"1542","ABT 1542":"about 1542","1562":"1562","1540":"1540","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Aldworth, Berkshire, England":"Aldworth, Berkshire, England","Boxford, Berkshire, England":"Boxford, Berkshire, England","Pangbourne, Berkshire, England":"Pangbourne, Berkshire, England","Shouldham, Norfolk, England":"Shouldham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Francis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Franceis</i>, modern French <i>François</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>, originally ‘Frank’, though later used to denote a Frenchman. The personal name owed much of its popularity during the Middle Ages to the fame of Saint Francis of Assisi (1181–1226), whose baptismal name was actually <i>Giovanni</i> but who was nicknamed <i>Francisco</i> because his father was absent in France at the time of his birth. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Francesco   and Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian   Franc  , and also their derivatives, e.g. Croatian <b>Francišković</b> (see   Francisco   4).","English: ethnic name from the Old French adjective <i>Franceis</i> ‘French’ (see 1 above).","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames, or an adoption of the non-Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferenc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Casimir, Iwan, Zbigniew.","Hungarian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), Slovenian, and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Ferenc</i>, a Hungarian form of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Fraczek","meanings":["Polish (<b>Frączek</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Franciszek</i>, an equivalent of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ). It is found mainly in Lesser Poland."]},{"name":"Chico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jesus, Pedro, Rafael, Bernardo, Camilo, Cirilo, Juan, Miguel, Ramona, Ruben.","Spanish: from <i>chico</i> ‘small, young’ (of uncertain origin, perhaps from Latin <i>ciccum</i> ‘trifle’), applied as a nickname for a small man, or for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name.","Portuguese: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francisco</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Francesco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Gabriele, Giovanni, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Carlota, Garcia, Romana.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Francesco</i> (from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>), an equivalent of   Francis  ."]},{"name":"Di Cicco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Pasquale, Carlo, Cosmo, Giovanni, Giulio, Giuseppe, Nicola, Attilio, Benedetto, Carmela.","Italian: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Ceccarelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Dino, Angelo, Dante, Quinto, Sesto, Aldo, Americo, Amerigo, Arcangelo, Augusto, Aurelio, Franco, Gino, Guido, Italo, Leoncio, Renato, Roberto, Tino, Tito, Valerio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Ceccarello</i>, a diminutive of <i>Cecco</i>, itself a diminutive <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Di Cioccio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Cosmo, Mario, Cesidio, Dante, Guido, Salvatore, Aldo, Americo, Benito, Biagio, Domenico, Ezio, Flavio, Nunzio, Quintino, Silverio.","Italian: patronymic from a personal name of uncertain derivation,possibly a pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cillo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Americo, Aniello, Antonio, Carmine, Gianna, Giovanni, Guido, Livio, Rocco, Vito.","Italian: from a shortened pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (equivalent of   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cisco","meanings":["Italian (Veneto): from the personal name <i>Cisco</i>, a short form of <i>Francesco</i>, Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","American shortened form of the surname   Francisco   (which is in part of German and presumably also of French origin) and thus a variant of   Sisco   and   Sesco  ."]},{"name":"Fran","meanings":["Croatian: from a short form of local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","Spanish: probably an altered form of Catalan   Franc  .","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): from a short form of the Spanish personal name   Franco   or   Francisco  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Francis was born in 1505, in Aldworth, Berkshire, England. She married Richard Knapp Sir in 1521, in Shouldham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 4 daughters.